body:
## Steps to reproduce the issue

```Verilog
module gen_test7;
	reg [2:0] out1;
	reg [2:0] out2;
	wire [2:0] out3;
	generate
		begin : cond
			initial begin : init
				reg signed [31:0] x;
				x = 2 ** 2;
				out1 = x;
			end
			always @* begin : proc
				reg signed [31:0] x;
				x = 2 ** 1;
				out2 = x;
			end
			genvar x;
			for (x = 0; x < 3; x = x + 1) // Trouble!
				assign out3[x] = 1;
		end
	endgenerate

// `define VERIFY
`ifdef VERIFY
	assert property (out1 == 4);
	assert property (out2 == 2);
	assert property (out3 == 7);
`endif
endmodule
```
```Verilog
module gen_test8;
	wire [1:0] x = 2'b11;
	generate
		begin : A
			begin : B
				wire [1:0] y = 2'b00;
			end
			begin : C
				wire [1:0] z = 2'b01;
			end
			wire [1:0] x = B.y ^ 2'b11 ^ C.z; // Trouble!
		end
	endgenerate

// `define VERIFY
`ifdef VERIFY
	assert property (x == 3);
	assert property (A.x == 2);
	assert property (A.C.z == 1);
	assert property (A.B.y == 0);
`endif
endmodule
```

## Expected behavior

Both modules should make it through the Verilog frontend successfully.

## Actual behavior

Both fail, but for different reasons.

I believe the first test case captures the same issue seen in #1456. The error is:
```
tests/simple/generate.v:183: ERROR: Left hand side of 1st expression of generate for-loop is not a gen var!
```

The second test case yields:
```
tests/simple/generate.v:207: Warning: Identifier `\B.y' is implicitly declared.
tests/simple/generate.v:207: Warning: Identifier `\C.z' is implicitly declared.
```
But `B.y` should resolve to `A.B.y` given the context of its usage.

I suspect some overhaul of the generate/block prefixing strategy might fix both of these issues.

